. According to data from Bespoke Investment Group, energy and materials were the top sector performers, each gaining over 2%. Tech, consumer discretionary, and communication services underperformed following last week‚Äôs strength.
The headliner event of the week will be a crucial two-day meeting of the Federal Reserve's policy-making committee, where central bank officials
whether to raise interest rates again or take a pause amid the turmoil in the banking sector.
Prior to the Silicon Valley Bank fallout, policy makers were poised to hike rates by as much as 50 basis points following a flurry of data showing a resilient economy. But given the crisis in the banking sector, many market participants forecast a smaller point increase ‚Äî or none at all.
‚ÄúBased on Powell‚Äôs recent hawkish shift in early March, the market is still giving the Fed room to hike 25bps at this upcoming meeting, but will not allow the Fed to get away with more tightening beyond that,‚Äù Victor Masotti, Director of Repo Trading at Clear Street, wrote in a statement.
The European Central Bank was confronted by a similar scenario on Thursday. As a result, the ECB raised interest rates by
saying it remains committed to dampening inflation while monitoring the turmoil in the banking sector.
‚ÄúOur economists expect the Fed to follow the ECB‚Äôs lead and raise rates in line with expectations, do away with forward guidance, but signal a continued tightening bias,‚Äù Jim Reid and colleagues at Deutsche Bank wrote in an early morning note Tuesday.
